00:52:59.120 --> 00:53:00.190
That's really compelling.

00:53:00.190 --> 00:53:02.890
The other thing that I
like to tell people about

00:53:02.890 --> 00:53:06.932
is a study that was done
by KPMG for Vodafone

00:53:06.932 --> 00:53:08.890
when they were trying to
look at their policies

00:53:08.890 --> 00:53:09.830
in all their countries.

00:53:09.830 --> 00:53:11.650
And they're not a huge presence
here in the United States,

00:53:11.650 --> 00:53:13.870
but they're very big in
Europe, in particular.

00:53:13.870 --> 00:53:18.619
And they looked at the
value of offering, it was--

00:53:18.619 --> 00:53:19.660
I want to get this right.

00:53:19.660 --> 00:53:21.340
It's six months of
paid leave-- maybe

00:53:21.340 --> 00:53:25.150
it's 16 weeks of paid leave, but
then also this gentle re-entry

00:53:25.150 --> 00:53:29.080
plan of paying for, I think, six
additional weeks of full-time

00:53:29.080 --> 00:53:32.440
pay at part-time
work upon return.

00:53:32.440 --> 00:53:34.390
And they found, when
they did the math on it,

00:53:34.390 --> 00:53:38.110
that it would save-- if every
private company in the world

00:53:38.110 --> 00:53:40.350
did this, it would
save $19 billion

00:53:40.350 --> 00:53:44.860
in money that is lost
from people leaving.

00:53:44.860 --> 00:53:47.690
Retention is
incredibly valuable,

00:53:47.690 --> 00:53:52.630
